texts.textentryhtml: Inspired by early twentieth-century experiments with cameraless photography, Rankaitis builds her pictures on photosensitive paper through the combination of exposures of photographic negatives, photogram silhouettes of objects, and passages of hand-painted photographic color dyes and pigments; the resulting work is a unique print—part photograph and part painting. Working collaboratively with molecular biologists and neuroscientists, Rankaitis’s pictures encode layered references to biological and ecological systems; the utilisateur final, or “final user,” is the endpoint, the person who completes such a system through his or her actions.
The artist. Acquired by Robert Mann and Orly Cogan; given to the Princeton University Art Museum, 2018.
